 to hostile metropolitan scrutiny. This book challenges traditional notions of a radical revolution in government, identifying a more profound and general transition from a metropolitan reliance on gossip and personal information to the embrace of new statistical forms of knowledge. The analysis moves between London, New South Wales and the Cape Colony, encompassing both government insiders and those who struggled against colonial and imperial governments.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aBritish government.  aBritish historiography.  aBritish imperialism.  acolonial governance.  acolonial lobbyists.  agovernors.  ahistorical networking.  aimperial administration.  aimperial policies.  ainformation networks.  ainformation revolution.  ametropolitan politics.  apatronage networks.  apersonal communications.  aprivate correspondence.  aunofficial correspondence.1 aLaidlaw, Zoë, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779440640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847794406423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847794406/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles